The paper deals with the state complexity of regular languages, which is a topic in formal language theory (cs.FL). The use of DFAs suggests a focus on automata theory and computational complexity (cs.DS). The paper also involves combinatorial arguments and counting techniques, which are common in discrete mathematics and combinatorics (cs.LO). The worst-case analysis of state complexity involves the study of lower bounds, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). Finally, the paper uses information theory to derive some of its results, which is a topic in information theory and coding theory (cs.IT).
